spans.text: what hollow blandishment and art They lead the winged captive to the snare
the winged captive to the snare
it is not Insolence that speaks
to greatness due Not the bribed sycophant more willing pays
Else our vain bark , without a rudder , floats The scorn and pastime of each veering gale
the rude inhabitants , whence tales Of listening woods
the full chorus lifting hymns to Jove
The sad reverse might start a gentle tear
those who never heard her name
A withered laurel , and a mouldering arch ! —
Where the soul riots with secure excess
Harmonious Virgil to his Mantuan farm , Or Baian
your clear steady mirror — in that glass The forms of good and ill are well portrayed
